    "heading_text": "What makes a dependency",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies/#what-makes-a-dependency",
    "chunk_index": 0,
    "chunk_text": "What makes a dependency. Up to now you have seen dependencies declared as functions. But that's not the only way to declare dependencies (although it would probably be the more common). The key factor is that a dependency should be a \"callable\". A \" callable \" in Python is anything that Python can \"call\" like a function. So, if you have an object something (that might not be a function) and you can \"call\" it (execute it) like: or then it is a \"callable\".",
    "token_count": 113,
    "kind": null,
    "title": null
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies::section-0004::chunk-0000",
    "chunk_kind": "heading",
    "source_node_id": "tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies::section-0004",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies::section-0001",
    "page_id": "tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies",
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "level": 2,
    "heading_text": "Classes as dependencies",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies/#classes-as-dependencies_1",
    "chunk_index": 0,
    "chunk_text": "Classes as dependencies. You might notice that to create an instance of a Python class, you use that same syntax. For example: In this case, fluffy is an instance of the class Cat . And to create fluffy , you are \"calling\" Cat . So, a Python class is also a callable . Then, in FastAPI , you could use a Python class as a dependency. What FastAPI actually checks is that it is a \"callable\" (function, class or anything else) and the parameters defined. If you pass a \"callable\" as a dependency in FastAPI , it will analyze the parameters for that \"callable\", and process them in the same way as the parameters for a path operation function . Including sub-dependencies. That also applies to callables with no parameters at all. The same as it would be for path operation functions with no parameters.",
    "token_count": 185,
    "kind": null,
    "title": null
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies::section-0004::chunk-0001",
    "chunk_kind": "heading",
    "source_node_id": "tutorial/dependencies/classes-as-dependencies::section-0004",
